    <stitle>STEERING COLUMN ASSEMBLY, TILT/TELESCOPING - DISASSEMBLE - UNIVERSAL JOINTS</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="disassemble" graphiccount="3">
        <title>UNIVERSAL JOINTS</title>
        <para>The universal joint at the steering gear may be removed and serviced separately. To service the upper
            universal joint, the steering column does not have to be removed.
        </para>
        <para>Once the shafts and universal joints are removed from the vehicle, the procedure for servicing the
            universal joint is as follows:
        </para>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>Do ot damage bearing surfaces.</para>
            </caution>
        </specpara>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Place universal joint in a vise (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500906">Figure 6</hotlnk>). Remove snap ring fitting in grooves of the spider bearings
                which locate them on the inside of the yokes. To remove snap rings, place a screwdriver against an end
                of the snap ring and push.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1"></para>
            <figure id="f0500906" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0500906" filename="../figg05/G0500906.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 6. Snap Ring Removal</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. BEARING</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. YOKE</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. SPIDER</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. SNAP RING</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <para>Place shaft assembly in vise with one yoke resting on the vise and the other yoke suspended with the
                bearing to be removed facing down (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500907">Figure 7</hotlnk>). Tap yoke beside bearing to be removed; bearing should walk
                out of the yoke.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f0500907" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g0500907" filename="../figg05/G0500907.webp" type="webp"/>
            <caption>Figure 7. Bearing Removal</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>1. BEARING</callout1>
                <callout1>2. YOKE</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">If the bearing does not come completely out, clamp bearing in vise. Use copper jaw covers on
                vise. Strike the yoke with a soft hammer and drive the yoke away from the bearing (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0500908">Figure 8</hotlnk>).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f0500908" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g0500908" filename="../figg05/G0500908.webp" type="webp"/>
            <caption>Figure 8. Bearing Removal</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>1. YOKE</callout1>
                <callout1>2. BEARING</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">With the bearings removed, the spider can be easily removed from the yoke.</para>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
